## Best Practices

### Scan-Friendly Formatting

- **Short lines:** Keep lines under 80 characters when possible
- **Consistent labels:** Always use the exact field names (Context, State, What I did, Next, Risks, ETA, Links)
- **Bullets:** Use checkbox bullets (`- [x]` or `- [ ]`) for action items
- **Whitespace:** Add blank lines between sections for readability

### Content Guidelines

- **Be specific:** "Added dark mode toggle component" not "Worked on feature"
- **Be concise:** Each action item should be one line
- **Update regularly:** Post updates every 30-60 minutes of active work
- **Surface blockers early:** Don't wait to report blockers - post immediately

### State Transitions

- **Starting → In Progress:** After first meaningful work item completed
- **In Progress → Blocked:** When encountering blockers or waiting for dependencies
- **Blocked → In Progress:** When blocker is resolved
- **In Progress → Done:** When all work items are complete and changes are committed/pushed

## Integration with Agent Workflows

### Implementation Agents

- Post status update when starting ticket work
- Post updates after completing each major milestone (planning, implementation, testing, verification)
- Post immediately when blocked
- Post final update when moving ticket to "Ready for QA"

### QA Agents

- Post status update when starting QA review
- Post updates after completing code review, testing, and artifact verification
- Post immediately when blocking issues are found
- Post final update when moving ticket to "Human in the Loop" or back to "To-do"

### PM Agents

- Post status update when starting ticket analysis or planning
- Post updates after completing research, ticket creation, or handoff
- Post immediately when clarification is needed
- Post final update when ticket is ready for implementation

## Scope

- **Applies to:** All agent types (Implementation, QA, PM, and future agent types)
- **Enforcement:** Status messages should follow this template format for consistency
- **Flexibility:** Template fields can be omitted if not applicable (e.g., "Risks: None" can be shortened to just "Risks: None" or omitted entirely if truly no risks)
